  "output": "## Performance Analysis — jobsquare\n\nThis is a Python async job-scraper (fetch → filter → dedupe → notify), not a web app — there's no React frontend, so I skipped that section. Here's what I found, ranked by impact.\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-74` (biggest win)\n\n`Store.diff()` issues one `SELECT` per job in a Python loop. Every pipeline run fetches hundreds–thousands of listings (Amazon/Microsoft/Netflix return up to `max_pages × 10`), so this is hundreds of round-trips to SQLite every run, every 12h.\n\n```python\n# current — N SELECTs\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    ...\n```\n\nFix: load all existing hashes once, diff in memory:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    existing = dict(self.conn.execute(\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs\"))\n    new, changed, seen = [], [], []\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = existing.get(job.key)\n        if h is None:\n            new.append(job); self._insert(cur, job, now)\n        elif h != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job); self._update(cur, job, now)\n        else:\n            seen.append(job.key)\n    if seen:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", [(now, k) for k in seen])\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\nTurns O(N) round-trips into 1 SELECT + batched writes.\n\n### 2. Redundant regex compilation — `filters.py:11-27`\n\n`filter_jobs` calls `match()` per job, and `match()` calls `_compile()` on every call — recompiling the same include/exclude keyword patterns from scratch for **every single job**. For N jobs × M keywords, that's O(N×M) regex compiles instead of O(M).\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    cutoff = None\n    max_age = rules.get(\"max_age_days\")\n    if max_age:\n        cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=float(max_age))\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                      locations=rules.get(\"locations\"), cutoff=cutoff)]\n```\nand change `match()`'s `include`/`exclude` params to accept pre-compiled `list[re.Pattern]` directly instead of raw strings.\n\n### 3. Missing index — `store.py:11-27`\n\n`added_since()` (called every `agent.py db-new`, i.e. every scan) does `WHERE first_seen > ? ORDER BY first_seen, company, title` but the schema only indexes `company`. That's a full table scan + sort on every scan, and the table only grows (no pruning of stale jobs).\n\n```sql\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_jobs_first_seen ON jobs(first_seen);\n```\n\n### 4. Redundant hash/key recomputation — `models.py:55-75`\n\n`Job.key` and `Job.content_hash` are plain `@property`s (SHA-256 over 4 fields), recomputed from scratch on every access. In `store.py`'s diff loop each job hits `.key` (SELECT), `.content_hash` (compare), then `to_row()` — which recomputes both `self.key` and `self.content_hash` again. That's 2× the hashing/formatting work needed.\n\n```python\ndef to_row(self) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    d = asdict(self)\n    d.pop(\"raw\", None)\n    d[\"key\"] = self.key                 # 2nd computation\n    d[\"content_hash\"] = self.content_hash  # 2nd computation\n    return d\n```\nSince `Job` uses `slots=True`, `functools.cached_property` needs an explicit slot for the cache:\n```python\n@dataclass(slots=True)\nclass Job:\n    ...\n    _key_cache: str = field(default=\"\", repr=False, compare=False)\n    _hash_cache: str = field(default=\"\", repr=False, compare=False)\n\n    @property\n    def key(self) -> str:\n        if not self._key_cache:\n            self._key_cache = f\"{self.source}:{self.company}:{self.external_id}\"\n        return self._key_cache\n```\n(Same pattern for `content_hash`.) Minor in isolation, but cheap to fix and compounds with fix #1 since the diff loop now touches each job's key/hash exactly once per call site.\n\n### 5. Caching opportunity — full re-fetch every run, no conditional requests\n\n`fetch_amazon`/`fetch_microsoft`/`fetch_netflix`/etc. (fetchers.py) re-fetch up to `max_pages × 10` listings from scratch on every scheduled run (every 12h per the recent commit), with no ETag/If-Modified-Since, and no early-stop against what's already in the store. Since these boards are explicitly sorted newest-first (`sort_by: \"timestamp\"`, `sort: \"recent\"`), most of each run refetches jobs you already have.\n\nTwo independent, additive fixes:\n- **HTTP-level**: send `If-None-Match`/`If-Modified-Since` where the ATS supports it (Greenhouse/Lever do); short-circuit on 304.\n- **App-level** (bigger win, needs threading store access into `fetch_all`): stop paginating a source as soon as a page's items are all already-known keys with unchanged content hash — you only need the *new* prefix of a newest-first-sorted list. This would cut an Amazon/Microsoft run from ~40 pages to typically 1-2 once the store is warm.\n\n### 6. Serialized blocking I/O in notify — `notify.py:105-109`\n\n`dispatch()` runs Slack/webhook/email/SMS notifiers sequentially with **synchronous** `httpx.post` (15s timeout each), even though `pipeline.run()` is already async. Worst case (Slack down + webhook down) stacks up to ~60s of blocking calls on a path that has async infrastructure sitting right there unused.\n\n```python\nasync def dispatch(new: list[Job], changed: list[Job]) -> None:\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient() as client:\n        results = await asyncio.gather(\n            *(fn(new, changed, client) for fn in NOTIFIERS), return_exceptions=True)\n    for fn, r in zip(NOTIFIERS, results):\n        if isinstance(r, Exception):\n            print(f\"  ! notifier {fn.__name__} failed: {r}\")\n```\n(requires converting each `notify_*` to accept/use the shared async client — `notify_email`'s `smtplib` call would need `asyncio.to_thread`).\n\n### Memory leaks\nNone found — process-scoped CLI runs (`cli.py`/`agent.py`) exit after each invocation, `httpx.AsyncClient` and the SQLite connection are both properly closed via context managers, and the PDF tmp file in `agent.py:219-228` is unlinked in a `finally`. Not a concern here.\n\n### Redundant computations — other notes\n`agent.py:137-152`'s `_ATS_RULES` are compiled once at module load — that's already the right pattern; contrast with filters.py above which isn't.\n\n---\nPriority order if you want me to implement: **#1 and #2 are the highest ROI for lowest risk** (self-contained, no architecture change) — want me to make those two changes now?\n",
